HEADWORD: Ditone
<hw>Di"tone`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ of two
tones; <grk>di-</grk> = <grk>di`s-</grk> twice + <?/ tone.]</ety>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The Greek major third, which comprehend two major
tones (the modern major third contains one major and one minor whole
tone).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ditrichotomous</ent>⟦br⟧
